<ue5><m0>Guards demanding resignation,<ql>
public inquiry over jail riot<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>WINNIPEG <m0>(--) Guards at Headingley Jail, the site last week of a bloody 24-hour riot, are demanding the province call a public inquiry and the Manitoba justice minister resign.<ep>
   About 250 of the guards met Thursday night before submitting a letter of their demands Friday. They want their demands met within 48 hours or some say they will not return to work at the ravaged jail.<ql>
<m1><ql>
<styl>rdup,17p8<ql>
<ue5><m0>Victim's families appeal ruling<ql>
to allow pornographic evidence<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>TORONTO<m0> (--) The families of two girls killed by Paul Bernardo have appealed a judge's dismissal of their bid to bar the public and media from courtrooms when pornographic evidence is presented.<ep>
   ``First and foremost we are dealing with Leslie Mahaffy and Kristen French, but the argument that we made would apply to all Canadian women and Canadian children,'' lawyer Tim Danson said Friday.<ep>
   The appeal of the ruling by Justice Patrick Gravely was filed with the Ontario Court of Appeal. The French and Mahaffy families complained to Gravely that their rights were violated each time videotapes of Bernardo raping the girls was played at his trial last summer.<ep>
   ``It's too late for us,'' Leslie Mahaffy's mother, Debbie, said Friday. But she said other families shouldn't have to go through the suffering.<ep>
   Gravely had ruled that it is up to individual judges to bar the public from seeing evidence.<ql>
