<ue5><m0>Premier Bouchard to try to sell<ql>
Americans on Quebec during visit<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0>  <m0>QUEBEC <m0>(--) Premier Lucien Bouchard will try to sell Americans on investing in Quebec when he visits New York next month.<ep>
    Bouchard will deliver a speech June 3 to the Foreign Policy Association.<m1><ep>
<m0>   The trip to New York is, in part, an attempt to assuage jittery international investors on Quebec's political future, but it also has domestic ramifications.<ep>
   After Quebec businessmen complained earlier this year that the prospect of another sovereignty referendum was hurting investment, Bouchard promised he would try to help.<ql>
<m1><ql>
<styl>rdup,17p8<ql>
<ue5><m0>Largest labor groups agree<ql>
to end their 14-year feud<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>OTTAWA <m0>(--) Canada's largest labor groups kissed and made up Friday, ending a sometimes bitter 14-year feud.<ep>
   The 2 million-member Canadian Labor Congress and the smaller Canadian Federation of Labor signed a cooperation agreement committing them to fight unemployment and economic policies that create it.<ep>
   ``Inter-union disputes within the labor movement waste resources which could be better spent elsewhere,'' said Jim McCambly, president of the 215,000-strong federation.<ep>
   McCambly helped create the federation in 1982, when several building trades unions broke away from the Labor Congress in a dispute about unions raiding each other for members.<ql>
